<exercises xml:id="s_Rn_ex">

<exercisegroup>
    <title>Vector space examples</title>
    
    
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Show that the given set together with the given operations constitutes a vector space by verifying that the vector axioms hold. Follow <xref ref="proc_vector_space"/>. In particular, explicitly identify what element of the set acts as the zero vector <m>\boldzero</m>, and how vector inverses of elements are defined. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <exercise xml:id="ex_infinite_sequences">
        <title>Infinite sequences</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Define <m>\R^\infty</m> to be the set of all infinite sequences: <ie/>, 
                <me>
                    \R^\infty=\{(a_i)_{i=1}^\infty\colon a_i\in \R\}
                </me>.
                Define vector addition and scalar multiplication as follows: 
                <md>
                    <mrow>(a_i)_{i=1}^\infty+(b_i)_{i=1}^\infty \amp = (a_i+b_i)_{i=1}^\infty </mrow>
                    <mrow>c(a_i)_{i=1}^\infty \amp = (ca_i)_{i=1}^\infty </mrow>
                </md>.
                In case you prefer the expanded notation for infinite sequences, we have: 
                <md>
                    <mrow>(a_1,a_2,\dots)+(b_1,b_2,\dots) \amp =(a_1+b_1,a_2+b_2,\dots)</mrow>
                    <mrow>c(a_1,a_2,\dots) \amp =(ca_1,ca_2,\dots)</mrow>
                </md>.  
            </p>
        </statement>
        
    </exercise>
    <exercise xml:id="ex_positive_reals">
        <title>Positive reals</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Define <m>\R_{&gt; 0}</m> to be the set of all positive real numbers: <ie/>, 
                <me>
                    \R_{&gt; 0}=\{r\in \R\colon r&gt; 0\}
                </me>.
                Define vector addition on <m>\R_{&gt; 0}</m> to be real number multiplication, and define scalar multiplication on <m>\R_{&gt; 0}</m> to be real number exponentiation: 
                <ie/>, given vectors <m>\boldv=r</m> and <m>\boldw=s</m> in <m>\R_{&gt; 0}</m>, and scalar <m>c\in \R</m>, we define 
                <md>
                    <mrow>\boldv\oplus\boldw \amp = r\, s</mrow>
                    <mrow>c\odot\boldv \amp = r^c </mrow>
                </md>.
                Note: we have introduced new notation for our vector operations to help distinguish them from familiar real number arithmetic operations. 
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>

</exercisegroup>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Prove statements (2)-(4) of <xref ref="th_vectorspace_props"/>. When treating a specific part you may assume the results of any part that has already been proven, including statement (1).
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>V</m> be a vector space.
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Show that the zero vector of <m>V</m> is unique: <ie />, show that if <m>\boldw\in V</m> satisfies <m>\boldw+\boldv=\boldv</m> for all <m>\boldv\in V</m>, then <m>\boldw=\boldzero</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Fix <m>\boldv\in V</m>. Show that the vector inverse of <m>\boldv</m> is unique: <ie />, show that if <m>\boldw+\boldv=\boldzero</m>, then <m>\boldw=-\boldv</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
    Thus we may speak of <em>the</em> zero vector of a vector space, and <em>the</em> vector inverse of a vector <m>\boldv</m>.
  </p>
  </statement>

</exercise>
<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>V</m> be a vector space.
      Prove:
      <me>\boldu + \boldw = \boldv + \boldw \iff \boldu=\boldv</me>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="ex_vs_zero_or_infinite">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>V</m> be a vector space. Prove that either <m>V=\{\boldzero\}</m> (<ie />, <m>V</m> is the zero space) or <m>V</m> is infinite. In other words, a vector space contains either exactly one element or infinitely many elements.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Assume <m>V</m> contains a nonzero vector <m>\boldv\ne\boldzero</m>. Show that if <m>c\ne d</m>, then <m>c\boldv\ne d\boldv</m>. You assume the results of <xref ref="th_vectorspace_props"/>.
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>

</exercises>
